              "content": "# Python Security Review Notes\n\n## Common Python Security Vulnerabilities\n\n### 1. Input Validation Issues\n- SQL Injection vulnerabilities\n- Command injection risks\n- Cross-site scripting (XSS)\n- Path traversal attacks\n\n### 2. Authentication & Authorization\n- Weak password handling\n- Session management flaws\n- Privilege escalation risks\n\n### 3. Data Protection\n- Insecure data storage\n- Insufficient encryption\n- Data leakage risks\n\n## Python Security Best Practices\n\n### Code Security\n- Use parameterized queries (prevent SQL injection)\n- Validate and sanitize all user inputs\n- Implement proper error handling\n- Use secure coding patterns\n\n### Dependency Management\n- Regularly update Python packages\n- Use virtual environments\n- Scan for vulnerable dependencies\n- Use trusted package sources\n\n### Configuration Security\n- Secure environment variables\n- Proper file permissions\n- Secure default configurations\n\n### Network Security\n- Use HTTPS for web applications\n- Implement proper CORS policies\n- Validate SSL/TLS certificates\n\n## Tools for Python Security\n\n### Static Analysis\n- Bandit (security linter)\n- Safety (dependency scanner)\n- PyCharm security inspections\n\n### Dynamic Analysis\n- OWASP ZAP for web apps\n- Custom security testing\n- Penetration testing\n\n## Recommended Actions\n\n1. Conduct regular security audits\n2. Implement automated security testing\n3. Train developers on secure coding\n4. Establish security review processes\n5. Monitor for new vulnerabilities\n\nNote: This document should be regularly updated as new security threats emerge and Python security practices evolve."
