        "final_answer": "Based on the external content you provided and general knowledge about prompt injection defenses, here are the main approaches to defending against prompt injection attacks:\n\n## Prompt Injection Defense Approaches\n\n1. **Input Filtering**\n   - Sanitizing and validating user inputs\n   - Detecting and blocking malicious patterns\n   - Character/pattern whitelisting and blacklisting\n\n2. **Output Monitoring**\n   - Real-time analysis of model outputs\n   - Detecting suspicious or unauthorized content\n   - Content moderation and filtering\n\n3. **Sandboxing**\n   - Running LLMs in isolated environments\n   - Restricting system access and capabilities\n   - Limiting network connectivity and file system access\n\n4. **Prompt Engineering**\n   - Designing robust system prompts\n   - Using delimiters and clear instructions\n   - Implementing role-based restrictions\n   - Adding verification steps in the prompt flow\n\n5. **Additional Common Defenses:**\n   - **Contextual filtering** - Monitoring the conversation context\n   - **Rate limiting** - Preventing abuse through request throttling\n   - **User authentication** - Verifying user identity and permissions\n   - **Model fine-tuning** - Training models to resist injection attempts\n   - **Multi-step verification** - Adding confirmation steps for sensitive operations\n\nThe most effective defense strategy typically involves a combination of these approaches rather than relying on any single method, as prompt injection attacks can be sophisticated and varied in nature.",
